|1960 || 390,000
|-
|1989 || 317,000
|-
|2008 || 384,400
|}

The city has a population of 384,400 spread over an area of {{convert|51788|dunam|km2|1}} (20 mi²), yielding a population density of 7,445 people per square kilometer (2,875 per square mile). According to the [[Israel Central Bureau of Statistics]] (CBS), as of June 2006 Tel Aviv's population is growing at an annual rate of 0.9%. It consists of 91.8% [[Jew]]s, 4.2% [[Arab]]s and 4.0% others ([[Christians]], [[Buddhists]]).<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://gis.cbs.gov.il/website/yishuvim/yishuvim_2005/XLS/bycode.xls |title=Tel Aviv Ethnic Breakdown |publisher=[[Israel Central Bureau of Statistics]] |date=2005-12-31 |format=Excel |accessdate=2007-07-07}}"Others" refers to non-Arab Christians and unclassified.</ref> The city is relatively multicultural, and languages such as [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]], [[Thai language|Thai]], [[Russian language|Russian]], [[Arabic]], [[French language|French]] and [[English language|English]] are often spoken aside Hebrew. According to some estimates, about 50,000 unregistered Asian [[foreign worker]]s live in the city.<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://migration.ucdavis.edu/MN/more.php?id=1041_0_5_0 |title=Migration News |accessdate=2007-05-22 |publisher=UC Davis}}</ref> Compared with other Westernised cities, crime in Tel Aviv is relatively low.<ref>{{citeweb |url=https://www.osac.gov/Reports/report.cfm?contentID=64217 |title=Israel 2007 Crime & Safety Report: Tel Aviv |accessdate=2008-01-26 |publisher=Overseas Security Advisory Agency}}</ref>

According to Tel Aviv-Yafo Municipality, the average income in the city is 20% above the national average, with an unemployment rate of 6.9%.<ref name="TA Stats">{{citeweb |url=http://64.233.183.104/search?q=cache:Fmggdk2FbeIJ:www.tel-aviv.gov.il/English/cityhall/geo/6167Area.pdf+http://www.tel-aviv.gov.il/English/cityhall/geo/6167Area.pdf&hl=en&ct=clnk&cd=1&gl=uk |title=Tel Aviv-Yafo in Numbers |publisher=Tel Aviv-Yafo Municipality |accessdate=2008-01-27 |date=July 2006}}</ref> The city's education standards are above the national average: of its 12th-grade students, 64.4% are eligible for [[Bagrut|matriculation certificates]], the qualification received by high school graduates.<ref name="TA Stats"/> The age profile is relatively even,  with 22.2% aged under 20, 18.5% aged 20–29, 24% aged 30–44, 16.2% aged between 45 and 59, and 19.1% older than 60.<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www1.cbs.gov.il/reader/shnaton/templ_shnaton_e.html?num_tab=st02_11x&CYear=2007 |title=Statistical Abstract of Israel 2007 |accessdate=2008-01-23 |publisher=[[Israel Central Bureau of Statistics]] }}</ref>

Tel Aviv's population reached a peak in the early 1960s at around 390,000, falling to 317,000 in the late 1980s as high property prices forced families out and deterred young couples from moving in.<ref name="profile" /> Since the mass immmigration from the former Soviet Union in the 1990s, the population has risen steadily.<ref name="profile" /> Today, the city's population is young and growing.<ref name="young">{{cite news |url=http://www.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1200572495562&pagename=JPost%2FJPArticle%2FShowFull |title=Tel Aviv getting younger |work=[[Jerusalem Post]] |date=2008-01-21 |accessdate=2008-01-31}}</ref> In 2006, 22,000&nbsp;people moved to the city, while only 18,500 left,<ref name="young" /> and many of the new families had young children. The population of Tel Aviv is expected to reach 450,000 by 2025; meanwhile, the average age of residents in the city fell from 35.8 in 1983 to 34 in 2008.<ref name="young" /> The population over age 65 stands at 14.6% compared with 19% in 1983.<ref name="young" />

===Religion===
[[Image:Tel Aviv Great Synagogue.jpg|thumb|The [[Great Synagogue (Tel Aviv)|Great Synagogue of Tel Aviv]] in the 1930s]]
Despite its image as a secular city, Tel Aviv has about a hundred synagogues, including historic buildings such as the [[Great Synagogue (Tel Aviv)|Great Synagogue]], established in the 1930s.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Jewish underground of Tel Aviv |url=http://www.ynet.co.il/english/articles/0,7340,L-3451146,00.html |work=Ynetnews |first=Udi |last=Michelson |date=2007-01-19 |accessdate=2008-03-16}}</ref> In recent years, a center for secular Jewish Studies and a "secular [[yeshiva]]" have opened in the city.<ref name=arfa>{{cite news
|last=Arfa
|first=Orit
|title=Jewish learning on the rise in Tel Aviv
|work=Jerusalem Post
|accessdate=2008-07-15
|date=2006-10-21
|url=http://www.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1159193467733&pagename=JPost/JPArticle/ShowFull
}}</ref> Tensions between religious and secular Jews before the gay pride parade ended in vandalization of a synagogue<ref name=cohen>{{cite news
|last=Cohen
|first=Avi
|title=Synagogue vandalized as gay parade controversy picks up steam
|work=Ynetnews
|accessdate=2008-07-15
|date=2006-11-02
|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3322809,00.html
}}</ref>

One of Tel Aviv's famous landmarks is the [[Hassan Bek Mosque]], on the beachfront. Jaffa is home to a sizable Muslim and Christian population. The number of churches has grown in recent years to accommodate the religious needs of diplomats and foreign workers.<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www.goisrael.com/Tourism_Euk/Destinations/Tel+Aviv/Tel+Aviv-Jaffa.htm |title=Tel Aviv-Jaffa |accessdate=2008-03-16 |publisher=Israeli Tourism Ministry}}</ref>

The Tel Aviv District is 93 percent Jewish, 1 percent Muslim, and 1 percent Christian.
The remaining 5 percent are not classified by religion.<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www1.cbs.gov.il/reader/shnaton/templ_shnaton_e.html?num_tab=st02_06x&CYear=2007 |title=Population by District, Sub-District and Religion | pulisher=Israel CBS |work=Statistical Abstract of Israel 2007 |format=pdf |date=2007 |accessdate=2008-04-02}}</ref>

==Economy==
[[Image:Ehad Haam stock exchange.JPG|thumb|Tel Aviv Stock Exchange]]
[[Image:Shuk hacarmel.JPG|thumb|Shuk HaCarmel market]]

Since Tel Aviv was built on sand dunes, farming was not profitable and maritime commerce was centered in [[Haifa]] and [[Ashdod]]. Instead, the city gradually developed as a center for scientific and technical research. In 1974, [[Intel]] opened its first overseas research and development operation in the city, and Tel Aviv emerged as a high-tech center in the 1990s.<ref name="Economist" /> Economic activities in the city account for about 15 percent of national employment and about 17 percent of [[GDP]].<ref name="profile" /> Forty percent of national employment in finance and 25 percent of national employment in business services is in the city.<ref name="profile" />

The economy of Tel Aviv has developed dramatically over the past decades. The city has been described as a flourishing technological center by ''[[Newsweek]]'' and a "miniature [[Los Angeles]]" by ''[[The Economist]]''.<ref name="Newsweek">{{cite journal|last=Levy |first=Stephen |coauthors=Matt Rees |title="Focus on Technology: The Hot New Tech Cities" |journal=[[Newsweek]] |date=1998-11-09}} <!-- (online: 1998-11-04) "Massive immigration from Russia in the early 90s brought the country a flood of computer scientists with advanced theoretical knowledge." --></ref><ref name="Economist">{{cite journal |url=http://www.economist.com/cities/findStory.cfm?city_id=TLV&folder=Facts-Figures#Economic_profile |title=Tel Aviv City Guide |accessdate=2007-05-28 |journal=[[The Economist]]}}</ref> Many computer scientists, their numbers increased by immigration from the former Soviet Union since the early 1990s, live and work in Tel Aviv. In 1998, the city was described  by [[Newsweek]] as one of the top 10&nbsp;most technologically influential cities in the world. Since then, high-tech industry in the Tel Aviv area has developed even more.<ref name="Newsweek" /> The Tel Aviv metropolitan area (including satellite cities such as [[Herzliya]] and [[Petah Tikva]]) is Israel's center of high-tech and is sometimes referred to as [[Silicon Wadi]].<ref name="Newsweek"/><ref name="mercer" />
Tel Aviv is home to the [[Tel Aviv Stock Exchange]] (TASE), Israel's only stock exchange, which has reached record heights since the 1990s.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.businessweek.com/globalbiz/content/jun2007/gb20070621_251927.htm?chan=top+news_top+news+index_global+business |title=Israel: A Hotbed of...Investment |work=[[BusinessWeek]] |date=2007-06-21 |accessdate=2007-07-07 |last=Sandler |first=Neal}}</ref> Many international venture-capital firms, scientific research institutes and high-tech companies are headquartered in the city. Industries in Tel Aviv include chemical processing, textile plants and food manufacturers.<ref name="Economist" /> The city's nightlife, cultural attractions and architecture attract tourists whose spending benefits the local economy.<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www.thomsonfly.com/en/destination_3863.html |title=Tel Aviv |accessdate=2007-07-19 |publisher=Thomsonfly}}</ref>

The Globalization and World Cities Study Group and Network (GaWC) at [[Loughborough University]]  has constructed an inventory of [[world cities]] based on their level of advanced producer services. The inventory lists Tel Aviv as having "strong evidence" of world city formation&mdash;the highest ranking for a Middle Eastern city with the exception of partly-European [[Istanbul]].<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www.lboro.ac.uk/gawc/citylist.html |title=Inventory of World Cities |publisher=[[Loughborough University]] |accessdate=2007-07-07}}</ref>

Nine of the fifteen Israeli billionaires live in Israel; four live in Tel Aviv or its suburbs, according to ''[[Forbes]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.forbes.com/lists/2007/10/07billionaires_The-Worlds-Billionaires_CountryOfCitizen_10.html |title=The World's Billionaires |accessdate=2007-07-07 |work=Forbes}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www.forbes.com/lists/2006/81/biz_06israel_Israels-Richest_land.html |title=Israel's 40 Richest |date=2006-12-09 |accessdate=2007-07-07 |work=Forbes |last=Bin-Nun |first=Boaz}}</ref> The [[cost of living]] in Israel is high, with Tel Aviv being its most expensive city to live in. According to [[Mercer Human Resource Consulting|Mercer]], a human resources consulting firm based in New York, as of 2008 Tel Aviv is the most expensive city in the Middle East and the 14th most expensive in the world. It falls just behind [[Singapore]] and [[Paris]] and just ahead of [[Sydney]] and [[Dublin]] in this respect. By comparison, [[New York City]] is 22nd.<ref name="mercer" />

== Culture==
===Tourism and recreation===
[[Image:Tel Aviv Beachs.jpg|thumb|250px|Tel Aviv beachfront skyline]]

As a [[Mediterranean]] city, Tel Aviv is a magnet for international tourism likened by some to [[Barcelona]].<ref name="indy" /> It was listed as a top international [[tourist destination|tourism destination]] by [[New York Magazine]]<ref name="The best weekend getaway">{{citeweb |url=http://nymag.com/travel/2007/spring/30638/|title=Club-hop until the sun comes up over the Mediterranean |accessdate=2007-04-15 |publisher=New York Magazine}}</ref> and the [[New York Times]].<ref name="Seizing the Day in Tel Aviv">{{citeweb |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/20/travel/20telaviv.html |title=Seizing the Day in Tel Aviv |accessdate=2008-07-20 |publisher=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> According to the Tel Aviv-Yafo Municipality, it has 44&nbsp;hotels with more than 5,800&nbsp;rooms.<ref name="TA Stats" /> Tel Aviv has been called "the city that never sleeps" because of its [[nightlife]] and 24-hour culture.<ref name="night">{{citeweb |url=http://www.tel-aviv-insider.com/nightlife-1.php |title=bars in Tel Aviv |accessdate=2007-07-19 |publisher=Tel Aviv Insider}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1191257245175&pagename=JPost%2FJPArticle%2FShowFull |title=TA Anglos make their own scene in city that never sleeps
|work=[[Jerusalem Post]] |accessdate=2008-02-04 |date=2007-10-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/travel/features/2008/02/16/show-tel-89520-20321363/ |title=Show & Tel |work=The Mirror |accessdate=2008-02-16 |date=2008-02-16}}</ref>

Tel Aviv's largest [[public park]] is [[Yarkon Park|Park HaYarkon]]. Other parks such as [[Gan Meir]] and [[Dubnow Park]] are located in the city center area. Seventeen&nbsp;percent of the city is covered in plants.<ref name="TA Stats" /> Dizengoff Center was Israel's first mall. Tel Aviv has branches of some of the world's leading hotels, among them the [[Crowne Plaza]], [[Sheraton Hotels and Resorts|Sheraton]], [[Dan]], [[Isrotel Tower|Isrotel]] and [[Hilton Hotels|Hilton]]. It is home to many museums, architectural and cultural sites, and city tours are available in different languages.<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://city-tour.co.il/ntextin.asp?psn=1109 |title=Tel Aviv bus tour |accessdate=2008-01-19 |publisher=Tel Aviv City Tours}}</ref> Apart from bus tours, there are architectural tours<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www.telavivarchitecture.com |title=Tel Aviv architecture tour |accessdate=2008-01-19 |publisher=TelAvivArchitecture.com }}</ref> and [[Segway]] tours<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www.segways.co.il/ |title=Tel Aviv segway tours |accessdate=2008-01-19 |publisher=Segways.co.il}}</ref> and walking tours.<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www.telaviv4fun.com/citywalks.html |title=Tel Aviv walking tours |accessdate=2008-01-19 |publisher=TelAviv4Fun.com}}</ref> The nightlife is particularly active around the beachfront [[promenade]]s because of its many [[nightclub]]s and [[Bar (establishment)|bars]]. The city has a wide variety of restaurants offering traditional Israeli dishes as well as international fare. More than 100&nbsp;[[sushi]] restaurants, the third highest concentration in the world, do business in the city, and an [[Italian food|Italian]] restaurant in Tel Aviv was called the best Italian restaurant outside of Italy by the Italian Ministry of Agriculture.<ref name="times" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3499855,00.html |title=Israel becomes sushi mecca |first=Sarit |last=Saradas-Trutino |work=Ynetnews |accessdate=2008-02-15 |date=2008-01-28}}</ref>

Tel Aviv is more accepting of lesbians, gays, bisexuals, and transgender-transsexuals than any other major city in the region and has a well established [[LGBT community]].<ref name=burden>{{cite news
|last=Burden
|first=Chas Newkey
|title=Tel Aviv, the final gay frontier
|work=Ynetnews
|accessdate=2008-07-15
|date=2007-01-08
|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3349664,00.html
}}</ref> The city hosts a [[gay pride parade|pride parade]] that attracts thousands annually and in early 2008 it hosted Israel's first sex festival.<ref name=kapshuk>{{cite news
|last=Kapshuk
|first=Yoav
|title=15,000 take part in Tel Aviv gay parade
