}}</ref>

===Arts and theater===
[[Image:Hichal hatarbut7.jpg|thumb|Fredric R. Mann Auditorium, Tel Aviv's largest theater]]
Tel Aviv is a major cultural center of Israel.<ref>{{citebook |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=wyPZRi9uYxUC&pg=PA196&dq=tel+aviv+israel+cultural+capital&ei=RzLpR9b5FouuzgSe2529CQ&sig=UMwFeSsVp3W3r8KgHp83v6sIW9Q |title=Emerging Nodes in the Global Economy: Frankfurt and Tel Aviv Compared |first=Felsenstein, Daniel |last=Schamp, Eike W. |publisher=Springer |date=2002 |accessdate=2008-03-25}}</ref> Eighteen of Israel's 35&nbsp;major centers for the performing arts are located in the city, including five of the country's nine large theaters, where 55[[percent|%]] of all performances in the country and 75%
of all attendance occurs.<ref name="profile" /><ref name="culture">{{citeweb |url=http://www.cityguide.travel-guides.com/city/125/culture/Middle-East/Tel-Aviv.html |title=Tel Aviv Culture |accessdate=2008-01-31 |publisher=TravelGuides.com}}</ref> The
[[Tel Aviv Performing Arts Center]] is the home of the Israeli Opera, where [[Plácido Domingo]] was house tenor between 1962 and 1965, and the [[Cameri Theater]].<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www.israel-opera.co.il/Eng/?CategoryID=220&ArticleID=146 |title=History and Architecture |publisher=Israel Opera |accessdate=2008-01-31}}</ref> With 3,000&nbsp;seats, the Fredric R. Mann Auditorium (''Heichal Hatarbut'') is the city's largest theater.<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www.hatarbut.co.il/English/about.htm |title=Mann Auditorium |accessdate=2008-01-31 |publisher=Hatarbut.co.il}}</ref> [[Habima Theater]], Israel's national theater, was closed down for renovations in early 2008. Enav Cultural Center is one of the newer additions to the cultural scene.<ref name="culture" /> Other theaters in Tel Aviv are the Gesher Theater and Beit Lessin Theater; Tzavta and Tmuna are smaller theaters that host musical performances and [[Fringe theatre|fringe]] productions. In Jaffa, the Simta and Notzar theaters specialize in fringe style.
[[Image:Suzanne Dellal Centre5.jpg|thumb|left|Suzanne Dellal Centre for Dance and Theatre in [[Neve Tzedek]]]]
Tel Aviv is home to a number of established [[dance]] centers and companies. The [[Batsheva Dance Company]], a contemporary dance troupe, as well as [[Bat Dor]] and the [[Israel Ballet]] are also headquartered in Tel Aviv.<ref name="culture" /> Tel Aviv's center for modern and classical dance is the Suzanne Dellal Center in [[Neve Tzedek]].<ref name=iexplore>{{cite web
|title=Tel Aviv Activities
|work=iExplore.com
|accessdate=2008-07-15
|url=http://www.iexplore.com/cityguides/Israel/Tel+Aviv/Activities
}}</ref>

Opera and classical music performances are held daily in Tel Aviv. Many of the world's leading [[Conducting|classical conductors]] and [[Solo (music)|soloists]] have performed on Tel Aviv stages.<ref name="culture" /> Tel Aviv's [[Yarkon Park|Park HaYarkon]] is sometimes used as a  popular venue for [[pop rock]] concerts.<ref name=travel>{{cite web
|title=Yarkon Park (Ganei Yehoshua)
|work=Professional Travel Guide
|accessdate=2008-07-15
|url=http://www.professionaltravelguide.com/tel-aviv/see-and-do/sightseeing/parks-gardens/yarkon-park-ganei-yehoshua-484281
}}</ref><ref name=shechnik>{{cite news
|last=Shechnik
|first=Raz
|title=Madonna to perform in Tel Aviv?
|work=Ynetnews
|accessdate=2008-07-15
|date=2008-05-11
|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3541724,00.html
}}</ref><ref name=brinn>{{cite news
|last=Brinn
|first=David
|title=New York Dolls join Morrissey bill in Park Hayarkon
|work=Jerusalem Post
|accessdate=2008-07-15
|date=2008-06-03
|url=http://www.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1212041463126&pagename=JPost/JPArticle/ShowFull
}}</ref>

The [[Cinematheque|Tel Aviv Cinemathèque]] screens art movies, premieres of short and full-length Israeli films, and hosts a variety of film festivals, among them the Festival of Animation, Comics and Caricatures, the Student Film Festival, the Jazz, Film and Videotape Festival and Salute to Israeli Cinema. The city has several [[Multiplex (movie theater)|multiplex cinema]]s.<ref name="culture" />

===Museums===
[[Image:Eretz Israel Museum2.jpg|thumb|widthpx|The [[Eretz Israel Museum]].]]
Israel is said to have the highest number of museums per capita of any country, three of the largest of which are in Tel Aviv.<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www.visit-tlv.co.il/eng.html |title=Museums and Galleries |publisher=Tel Aviv Municipality |accessdate=2007-09-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Governing Israel: Chosen People, Promised Land and Prophetic Tradition  |last=Sharkansky |first=Ira |year=2005 |publisher=Transaction Publishers |isbn=0765802775 |pages=22 }}</ref>  Among these are the [[Eretz Israel Museum]], known for its collection of archaeology and history exhibits dealing with the [[Land of Israel]], and the [[Tel Aviv Museum of Art]]. Housed on the campus of [[Tel Aviv University]] is the [[Beth Hatefutsoth]], a museum of the international Jewish diaspora that tells the story of Jewish prosperity and persecution throughout the [[Jewish diaspora|centuries of exile]]. Batey Haosef Museum specializes in [[Israel Defense Forces]]' military history. The [[Palmach|Palmach Museum]] near Tel Aviv University offers a multimedia experience of the history of the Palmach as well as archives depicting the lives of Jewish soldiers who became Israel's first defenders. Near [[Charles Clore]]'s garden in north Jaffa is a small museum of the [[Irgun|Etzel]] Jewish militant organization, which conquered Jaffa in the [[1948 Arab-Israeli War]]. The [[Tel Aviv Exhibition Centre|Tel Aviv Exhibition Center]] in the northern part of the city hosts more than 60&nbsp;major events a year. Many offbeat museums and galleries operate in the city's southern areas, including the Tel Aviv Raw Art contemporary art gallery.<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www.tel-aviv.gov.il/English/culture/museums/index.htm |title=Treasure of the State |accessdate=2008-01-26 |publisher=Tel Aviv-Yafo Municipality}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www.tel-aviv.gov.il/English/culture/museums/list.htm |title=The Museums of Tel-Aviv-Jaffa |accessdate=2008-01-26 |publisher=Tel Aviv-Yafo Municipality}}</ref>

===Sports===
[[Image:NokiaArena.jpg|thumb|Tel Aviv's [[Nokia Arena]]]]
Tel Aviv is home to some of the top sports teams in Israel, including a world-class basketball team. It is the only city with three&nbsp;teams in [[Ligat ha'Al]], the country's top [[Football in Israel|football]] league. [[Maccabi Tel Aviv|Maccabi Tel Aviv Sports Club]] was founded in 1906 and competes in more than 10&nbsp;sports. Its [[Maccabi Tel Aviv B.C.|Maccabi Tel Aviv Basketball Club]] holds 47&nbsp;Israeli titles, has won 36&nbsp;editions of the Israel cup, and has five&nbsp;European Championships, and its [[Maccabi Tel Aviv F.C.]] holds 18&nbsp;Israeli league titles and has won 22&nbsp;editions of the Israel cup,  two&nbsp;Israel Toto cups and two&nbsp;Asia cups. [[Yael Arad]], an athlete in Maccabi's [[judo]] club, won a silver medal in the 1992 [[Olympic Games]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Great Jews in Sports |url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GWE_lEPfHpIC&pg=PA19&lpg=PA19&dq=yael+arad+olympics+tel+aviv&source=web&ots=LIDp37r1g8&sig=VY6aPXvzPszPVDfNvp1v5JBc3fc&hl=en|accessdate=2008-03-15 |publisher=Jonathan David Company, Inc. |first=Robert |last=Slater |date=2003 |pages=19}}</ref>

[[Hapoel Tel Aviv]] Sports Club was founded in 1923 and has included more than 11&nbsp;sports clubs<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www.fotw.net/flags/il@hapta.html |title=Hapoel Tel Aviv |accessdate=2007-07-19 |publisher=Fotw.net}}</ref> including the [[Hapoel Tel Aviv F.C.|Hapoel Tel Aviv Football Club]] (13&nbsp;Israeli championships, 11&nbsp;Israeli cups, one&nbsp;Toto cup and one&nbsp;Asia champion), a kayaking club, and a women's basketball club.
[[Image:Ramat Gan Stadium.jpg|thumb|left|widthpx|[[Ramat Gan Stadium]].]]
[[Bnei Yehuda Tel Aviv F.C.|Bnei Yehuda Tel Aviv]]'s football club (once Israeli champion, twice [[Israel State Cup|State Cup]] winners and twice [[Toto Cup]] winner) is the only Israeli football team in the top division that represents a neighborhood, the [[Hatikva Quarter]] in Tel Aviv, and not a city.

Tel Aviv is also the home to [[Hapoel Ussishkin]], a fan-owned basketball team founded in 2007 due to disagreements between the Hapoel Tel Aviv basketball team's management and the team's fans.

Other football clubs in the top division were [[Shimshon Tel Aviv F.C.|Shimshon Tel Aviv]] and [[Beitar Tel Aviv F.C.|Beitar Tel Aviv]], which has merged into one team, [[Beitar/Shimshon Tel Aviv F.C.|Beitar/Shimshon Tel Aviv]], in the third division, [[Liga Artzit]]. Another former first division team, [[Maccabi Jaffa F.C.|Maccabi Jaffa]], played in the lower divisions in the [[2007/08 in Israeli football|2007&ndash;08 season]].

Two [[rowing (sport)|rowing]] clubs operate in Tel Aviv. The Tel Aviv Rowing Club, established as early as 1935 on the banks of the Yarkon River, is the largest rowing club in Israel.<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www.rowersalmanac.com/profiles/israel.asp |title=Rowers Almanac |accessdate=2007-07-19 |publisher=Rowersalmanac.com}}</ref> Meanwhile, the beaches of Tel Aviv provide a vibrant [[Matkot]] (beach paddleball) scene.<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www.telaviv-insider.co.il/sports.php |title=Sports in the Tel-Aviv |accessdate=2007-07-19 |publisher=Tel Aviv Insider}}</ref> [[Tel Aviv Lightning]] represent Tel Aviv in the [[Israel Baseball League]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stljewishlight.com/topstories/12348156495807.php |title=Israel Baseball League starts in June |work=[[St. Louis]] Jewish Light |accessdate=2008-01-19}}</ref>

== Government ==
[[Image:Tel Aviv Court House Shaul Hamelech.JPG|thumb|Tel Aviv Courthouse]]
Tel Aviv is governed by a 31-member city council elected for a four-year term in direct proportional elections.<ref name="govt">{{cite book
  |last=Encyclopaedia Britannica Staff
  |first=
  |authorlink=
  |coauthors=
  |title=The New Encyclopaedia Britannica
  |publisher=Encyclopaedia Britannica
  |date=1974
  |location=
  |pages=66
  |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=YpZpY9plD7AC&q=tel-aviv+city+council&dq=tel-aviv+city+council&lr=&pgis=1
  |doi=
  |id=
  |isbn=0852292902}}</ref> All Israeli citizens over the age of 18 with at least one year of residence in Tel Aviv are eligible to vote in municipal elections. The municipality is responsible for social services, community programs, public infrastructure, urban planning, tourism and other local affairs.<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www.tel-aviv.gov.il/English/human/index.htm|title=Social Services Administration|accessdate=2008-03-29|publisher=Tel Aviv-Yafo Municipality}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www.tel-aviv.gov.il/English/education/community/centers.htm |title=Community Life |accessdate=2008-03-29 |publisher=Tel Aviv-Yafo Municipality}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www.tel-aviv.gov.il/English/Tourism/Information/Index.htm |title=Tourism |accessdate=2008-03-29 |publisher=Tel Aviv-Yafo Municipality}}</ref> The Tel Aviv City Hall is located at [[Rabin Square]]. As of 2008, [[Ron Huldai]] is mayor of Tel Aviv, having held that office since 1998.<ref name="govt" /> The longest serving mayor of the city was [[Shlomo Lahat]], who was in office for 19&nbsp;years. The shortest serving was [[David Bloch]], in office for just two years, 1925&ndash;27. The importance of Tel Aviv is further enhanced by the non-recognition of [[Jerusalem]] as the [[Positions on Jerusalem|Capital of Israel]] by the international community, which maintains  [[embassies]] mostly in Tel Aviv.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.science.co.il/Embassies.asp |title=Embassies and Consulates in Israel |publisher=Israel Science and Technology Homepage |accessdate=2008-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Society and Settlement: Jewish Land of Israel in the Twentieth Century |last=Kellerman |first=Aharon |isbn=0791412954 |publisher=State University of New York Press |month=January |year=1993 |pages=140 |quote=[Tel Aviv] also contains most embassies, given the nonrecognition by many countries of Jerusalem as the capital of Israel.}}</ref> The Israeli [[Ministry of Defense (Israel)|Ministry of Defense]] is in Tel Aviv.<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://israel.org/MFA/MFAArchive/1990_1999/1999/8/Ministry%20of%20Defense |title=Ministry of Defense |publisher=Israel Ministry of Foreign Affairs |date=1999-08-24 |accessdate=2008-03-18}}</ref> [[Israel Meir Lau]] is chief rabbi of the city.

The demographic split in the city has also created political divisions between the [[Labor Party (Israel)|Labor Party]], usually strongest in the north, and Likud and other right-wing and religious parties, usually strongest in the south.<ref name="Economist" /> In the [[Israeli legislative election, 2006|2006 election]], however this pattern changed when the new centrist [[Kadima]] party gained 28 percent of the city's vote, followed by [[Labor Party (Israel)|Labor]] with 20 percent.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-3233587,00.html |title=תוצאות האמת: 28 לקדימה, הליכוד במקום חמישי |publisher=Yedioth Ahronoth |date=2006-03-29 |accessdate=2008-03-30 |language=Hebrew}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?c=JPArticle&cid=1143498754035&pagename=JPost%2FJPArticle%2FShowFull |title=Pensioners a big hit in Tel Aviv |work=[[Jerusalem Post]] |accessdate=2008-03-30 |date=2006-03-29}}</ref>

